In the coming months, there will be all sorts of commemoration of the end of communism, including the anniversary of the fall of the Berlin Wall in November 1989.
For many people, it was an hour of glory, emblematic of the West's victory at the end of the Cold War, a victory from which no one knew the source.
But by witnessing the collapse of the Eastern Bloc from the beginning, one realizes that the process was long and complex.
The election in Poland was a point of no return, the moment where the movement in favor of change became irreversible.
He had gained strength after a summer of strikes, when the Communist leader of Poland, General Jaruzelski, concluded that the country's economic problems were too serious for him to tackle alone.
He wondered why not turn to the Polish opposition - if only to find a solution, at least to share the responsibility for the situation.
After six months of negotiations, he concluded a historic agreement: there would be free and fair legislative elections, and Solidarność could participate in them.
The communist leaders (no more than Solidarność) ever considered for a moment that they could lose.
Even in their darkest nightmares, they never imagined that they would be chased from power.
However, that is what happened.
Retrospectively, it is surprising that there could have been any doubts.
Solidarity ran its campaign with courage.
A famous spoof poster, adapted for the occasion from a classic Western, The Train Whistled Three Times, enjoyed great success: it shows Gary Cooper holding a ballot instead of a revolver, playing the role of the sheriff.
June 4th was the day of the final judgment.
On this bright Sunday morning, as spring was giving birth to summer, voters sent the Polish communists to the slaughterhouse.
For their last day in power, the Polish communists resorted to one final perversity that turned into an unintentional self-humiliation.
They designed an electoral system in which Poles, instead of choosing the candidates of their choice, had to cross off the names of those they did not want - which amounted to crossing off all the communists listed on the ballots.
Everywhere one looked, people were getting rid of the hated autocrats.
This was finally the popular uprising that Poland had been waiting for for a long time, the revenge against December 1980, when Jaruzelski declared martial law, banned Solidarność and threw its leaders in prison.
The revolution with the pen!
Manipulated with style, the pen that ultimately triumphs over the sword becomes the weapon of a glorious revenge.
Some voters were tearing their ballots to shreds, thus effectively giving a handy strike to the old regime.
Others were savoring the moment, perhaps smoking a cigarette while crossing off names on the ballots.
